# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: storybook-ui
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:storybook-ui/component-based-software-engineering] To find the right level of component granularity, software architects have to continuously iterate their component designs with developers.
[src:storybook-ui/component-based-software-engineering] Architects need to take into account user requirements, responsibilities, and architectural characteristics.
[src:storybook-ui/component-based-software-engineering] CBSE grew out of earlier paradigms such as structured programming and object-oriented programming, but it places greater emphasis on building software by assembling and integrating pre-existing components.
[src:storybook-ui/component-based-software-engineering] Unlike objects, which typically encapsulate both data and behavior, components are higher-level constructs that provide well-defined interfaces and can be deployed independently.
[src:storybook-ui/component-based-software-engineering] Component orientation underlies many modern software frameworks and architectural styles, including service-oriented architecture (SOA), microservices, and widely used frontend frameworks such as React, Angular, and Vue.
[src:storybook-ui/component-based-software-engineering] For large-scale systems developed by large teams, a disciplined culture and process is required to achieve the benefits of CBSE.
[src:storybook-ui/component-based-software-engineering] Third-party components are often utilized in large systems, raising issues of integration, licensing, and software quality.
[src:storybook-ui/component-based-software-engineering] The system can be designed visually with the Unified Modeling Language (UML).
[src:storybook-ui/component-based-software-engineering] Each component is shown as a rectangle, and an interface is shown as a lollipop to indicate a provided interface and as a socket to indicate consumption of an interface.
[src:storybook-ui/component-based-software-engineering] This graphical representation helps clarify the relationships and dependencies between components.
[src:storybook-ui/component-based-software-engineering] Component-based usability testing is applied when components interact directly with the end user, ensuring both functionality and user experience are preserved when components are reused or replaced.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] A **graphical user interface**, or **GUI**, is a form of user interface that allows users to interact with electronic devices through graphical icons and visual indicators such as secondary notation.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] In many applications, GUIs are used instead of text-based UIs, which are based on typed command labels or text navigation.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] GUIs were introduced in reaction to the perceived steep learning curve of command-line interfaces (CLIs), which require commands to be typed on a computer keyboard.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The actions in a GUI are usually performed through direct manipulation of the graphical elements.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Beyond computers, GUIs are used in many handheld mobile devices such as MP3 players, portable media players, gaming devices, smartphones and smaller household, office and industrial controls.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Designing the visual composition and temporal behavior of a GUI is an important part of software application programming in the area of human–computer interaction.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Its goal is to enhance the efficiency and ease of use for the underlying logical design of a stored program, a design discipline named *usability*.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Methods of user-centered design are used to ensure that the visual language introduced in the design is well-tailored to the tasks.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The visible graphical interface features of an application are sometimes referred to as *chrome* or *GUI*.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Typically, users interact with information by manipulating visual widgets that allow for interactions appropriate to the kind of data they hold.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The widgets of a well-designed interface are selected to support the actions necessary to achieve the goals of users.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] A model–view–controller allows flexible structures in which the interface is independent of and indirectly linked to application functions, so the GUI can be customized easily.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] This allows users to select or design a different *skin* or *theme* at will, and eases the designer's work to change the interface as user needs evolve.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Good GUI design relates to users more, and to system architecture less.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Large widgets, such as windows, usually provide a frame or container for the main presentation content such as a web page, email message, or drawing.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Smaller ones usually act as a user-input tool.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] A GUI may be designed for the requirements of a vertical market as application-specific GUIs.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Cell phones and handheld game systems also employ application specific touchscreen GUIs.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Newer automobiles use GUIs in their navigation systems and multimedia centers, or navigation multimedia center combinations.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] A GUI uses a combination of technologies and devices to provide a platform that users can interact with, for the tasks of gathering and producing information.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] A series of elements conforming a visual language have evolved to represent information stored in computers.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] This makes it easier for people with few computer skills to work with and use computer software.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The most common combination of such elements in GUIs is the *windows, icons, text fields, canvases, menus, pointer* (WIMP) paradigm, especially in personal computers.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The WIMP style of interaction uses a virtual input device to represent the position of a pointing device's interface, most often a mouse, and presents information organized in windows and represented with icons.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Available commands are compiled together in menus, and actions are performed making gestures with the pointing device.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] A window manager facilitates the interactions between windows, applications, and the windowing system.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The windowing system handles hardware devices such as pointing devices, graphics hardware, and positioning of the pointer.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] In personal computers, all these elements are modeled through a desktop metaphor to produce a simulation called a desktop environment in which the display represents a desktop, on which documents and folders of documents can be placed.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Window managers and other software combine to simulate the desktop environment with varying degrees of realism.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Entries may appear in a list to make space for text and details, or in a grid for compactness and larger icons with little space underneath for text.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Variations in between exist, such as a list with multiple columns of items and a grid of items with rows of text extending sideways from the icon.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Multi-row and multi-column layouts commonly found on the web are "shelf" and "waterfall".
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The former is found on image search engines, where images appear with a fixed height but variable length, and is typically implemented with the CSS property and parameter `display: inline-block;`.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] A waterfall layout found on Imgur and TweetDeck with fixed width but variable height per item is usually implemented by specifying `column-width:`.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Smaller app mobile devices such as personal digital assistants (PDAs) and smartphones typically use the WIMP elements with different unifying metaphors, due to constraints in space and available input devices.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Applications for which WIMP is not well suited may use newer interaction techniques, collectively termed *post-WIMP* UIs.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] As of 2011, some touchscreen-based operating systems such as Apple's iOS (iPhone) and Android use the class of GUIs named post-WIMP.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] These support styles of interaction using more than one finger in contact with a display, which allows actions such as pinching and rotating, which are unsupported by one pointer and mouse.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] There are also actions performed by programs that affect the GUI.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] For example, there are components like inotify or D-Bus to facilitate communication between computer programs.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Ivan Sutherland developed Sketchpad in 1963, widely held as the first graphical computer-aided design program.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] It used a light pen to create and manipulate objects in engineering drawings in realtime with coordinated graphics.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] In the late 1960s, researchers at the Stanford Research Institute, led by Douglas Engelbart, developed the On-Line System (NLS), which used text-based hyperlinks manipulated with a then-new device: the mouse.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Most modern general-purpose GUIs are derived from this system.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The Xerox PARC GUI consisted of graphical elements such as windows, menus, radio buttons, and check boxes.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The concept of icons was later introduced by David Canfield Smith, who had written a thesis on the subject under the guidance of Kay.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The PARC GUI employs a pointing device along with a keyboard.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] These aspects can be emphasized by using the alternative term and acronym for *windows, icons, menus, pointing device* (WIMP).
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] This effort culminated in the 1973 Xerox Alto, the first computer with a GUI, though the system never reached commercial production.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The first commercially available computer with a GUI was the 1979 PERQ workstation, manufactured by Three Rivers Computer Corporation.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Its design was heavily influenced by the work at Xerox PARC.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] In 1981, Xerox eventually commercialized the ideas from the Alto in the form of a new and enhanced system – the Xerox 8010 Information System – more commonly known as the Xerox Star.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Visi On was released in 1983 for the IBM PC compatible computers, but was never popular due to its high hardware demands.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Nevertheless, it was a crucial influence on the contemporary development of Microsoft Windows.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Apple, Digital Research, IBM and Microsoft used many of Xerox's ideas to develop products, and IBM's Common User Access specifications formed the basis of the GUIs used in Microsoft Windows, IBM OS/2 Presentation Manager, and the Unix Motif toolkit and window manager.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] These ideas evolved to create the interface found in current versions of Microsoft Windows, and in various desktop environments for Unix-like operating systems, such as macOS and Linux.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Thus most current GUIs have largely common idioms.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The early 1980s saw growing interest in GUIs.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The Apple Lisa was released in 1983, but was expensive and commercially unsuccessful.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Individual applications for many platforms presented their own GUI variants.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Despite the GUI's advantages, many reviewers questioned the value of the entire concept, citing hardware limits and problems in finding compatible software.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] In 1984, Apple introduced the Macintosh via the "1984" television commercial during Super Bowl XVIII, with allusions to George Orwell's novel *Nineteen Eighty-Four*.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The goal of the commercial was to make people think about computers, identifying the user-friendly interface as a personal computer which departed from prior business-oriented systems, and becoming a signature representation of Apple products.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The 1985 Atari ST shipped with the GEM GUI from Digital Research, which was also published for MS-DOS.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The Amiga 1000 was released the same year, though not widely available until 1986, with the Workbench graphical desktop.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] This interface ran as a separate task, meaning it was very responsive and, unlike other GUIs of the time, it did not freeze up when a program was busy.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Windows 95, accompanied by an extensive marketing campaign, was a major success in the marketplace at launch and shortly became the most popular desktop operating system.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] In 2007, with the iPhone and later in 2010 with the introduction of the iPad, Apple popularized the post-WIMP style of interaction for multi-touch screens, and those devices were considered to be milestones in the development of mobile devices.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The GUIs familiar to most people as of the mid-late 2010s are Windows, macOS, and the X Window System interfaces for desktop and laptop computers, and Android, Apple's iOS, Symbian, BlackBerry OS, Windows Phone/Windows 10 Mobile, Tizen, WebOS, and Firefox OS for handheld (smartphone) devices.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Since the commands available in command line interfaces can be many, complex operations can be performed using a short sequence of words and symbols.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Custom functions may be used to facilitate access to frequent actions.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Command-line interfaces are more lightweight, as they only recall information necessary for a task; for example, no preview thumbnails or graphical rendering of web pages.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] This allows greater efficiency and productivity once many commands are learned.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] But reaching this level takes some time because the command words may not be easily discoverable or mnemonic.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Also, using the command line can become slow and error-prone when users must enter long commands comprising many parameters or several different filenames at once.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] However, *windows, icons, menus, pointer* (WIMP) interfaces present users with many widgets that represent and can trigger some of the system's available commands.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] GUIs can be made quite hard when dialogs are buried deep in a system or moved about to different places during redesigns.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Also, icons and dialog boxes are usually harder for users to script.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] WIMPs extensively use modes, as the meaning of all keys and clicks on specific positions on the screen are redefined all the time.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Command-line interfaces use modes only in limited forms, such as for current directory and environment variables.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Most modern operating systems provide both a GUI and some level of a CLI, although the GUIs usually receive more attention.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] GUI wrappers find a way around the command-line interface versions (CLI) of (typically) Linux and Unix-like software applications and their text-based UIs or typed command labels.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] While command-line or text-based applications allow users to run a program non-interactively, GUI wrappers atop them avoid the steep learning curve of the command-line, which requires commands to be typed on the keyboard.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] By starting a GUI wrapper, users can intuitively interact with, start, stop, and change its working parameters, through graphical icons and visual indicators of a desktop environment, for example.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Applications may also provide both interfaces, and when they do the GUI is usually a WIMP wrapper around the command-line version.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] This is especially common with applications designed for Unix-like operating systems.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The latter used to be implemented first because it allowed the developers to focus exclusively on their product's functionality without bothering about interface details such as designing icons and placing buttons.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Designing programs this way also allows users to run the program in a shell script.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Many environments and games use the methods of 3D graphics to project 3D GUI objects onto the screen.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The use of 3D graphics has become increasingly common in mainstream operating systems (ex.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Windows Aero, and Aqua (macOS)) to create attractive interfaces, termed eye candy (which includes, for example, the use of drop shadows underneath windows and the cursor), or for functional purposes only possible using three dimensions.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] For example, user switching is represented by rotating a cube with faces representing each user's workspace, and window management is represented via a Rolodex-style flipping mechanism in Windows Vista (see Windows Flip 3D).
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] In both cases, the operating system transforms windows on-the-fly while continuing to update the content of those windows.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] The GUI is usually WIMP-based, although occasionally other metaphors surface, such as those used in Microsoft Bob, 3dwm, File System Navigator, File System Visualizer, 3D Mailbox, and GopherVR.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Zooming (ZUI) is a related technology that promises to deliver the representation benefits of 3D environments without their usability drawbacks of orientation problems and hidden objects.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] In 2006, Hillcrest Labs introduced the first ZUI for television.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] Augmented reality and virtual reality also make use of 3D GUI elements.
[src:storybook-ui/graphical-user-interface] 3D GUIs have appeared in science fiction literature and films, even before certain technologies were feasible or in common use.
[src:storybook-ui/storybookjs-storybook] Storybook is a frontend workshop for building UI components and pages in isolation.
[src:storybook-ui/storybookjs-storybook] Thousands of teams use it for UI development, testing, and documentation.
[src:storybook-ui/storybookjs-storybook] Visit Storybook's website to learn more about Storybook and to get started.
[src:storybook-ui/storybookjs-storybook] Documentation can be found on Storybook's docs site.
[src:storybook-ui/storybookjs-storybook] View Component Encyclopedia to see how leading teams use Storybook.
[src:storybook-ui/storybookjs-storybook] Use storybook.new to quickly create an example project in Stackblitz.
[src:storybook-ui/storybookjs-storybook] Storybook comes with a lot of addons for component design, documentation, testing, interactivity, and so on.
[src:storybook-ui/storybookjs-storybook] Storybook's API makes it possible to configure and extend in various ways.
[src:storybook-ui/storybookjs-storybook] It has even been extended to support React Native, Android, iOS, and Flutter development for mobile.
[src:storybook-ui/storybookjs-storybook] For additional help, share your issue in the repo's GitHub Discussions.
[src:storybook-ui/storybookjs-storybook] To continue improving your experience, we have to eventually deprecate or remove certain addons in favor of new and better tools.
[src:storybook-ui/storybookjs-storybook] If you're using info/notes, we highly recommend you migrate to docs instead, and here is a guide to help you.
[src:storybook-ui/storybookjs-storybook] If you're using contexts, we highly recommend you migrate to toolbars and here is a guide to help you.
[src:storybook-ui/storybookjs-storybook] If you're using addon-storyshots, we highly recommend you migrate to the Storybook test-runner and here is a guide to help you.
[src:storybook-ui/storybookjs-storybook] If you're looking for material to use in your Storybook presentation, such as logos, video material, and the colors we use, you can find it all on our brand repo.
[src:storybook-ui/storybookjs-storybook] Contributions to Storybook are always welcome!
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] User interfaces are the points of interaction between users and designs.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Users interact with visual representations on a computer's screen.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Users interact with these through their voices.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] on smartphones or Alexa on Amazon devices, use voice control.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Interface design is involved in a wide range of projects, from computer systems, to cars, to commercial planes; all of these projects involve much of the same basic human interactions yet also require some unique skills and knowledge.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] As a result, designers tend to specialize in certain types of projects and have skills centered on their expertise, whether it is software design, user research, web design, or industrial design.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Good user interface design facilitates finishing the task at hand without drawing unnecessary attention to itself.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Graphic design and typography are utilized to support its usability, influencing how the user performs certain interactions and improving the aesthetic appeal of the design; design aesthetics may enhance or detract from the ability of users to use the functions of the interface.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The design process must balance technical functionality and visual elements (e.g., mental model) to create a system that is not only operational but also usable and adaptable to changing user needs.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] User interface design is a craft in which designers perform an important function in creating the user experience.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] UI design should keep users informed about what is happening, giving appropriate feedback in a timely manner.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The visual look and feel of UI design sets the tone for the user experience.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] On the other hand, the term UX design refers to the entire process of creating a user experience.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] User interface design requires a good understanding of user needs.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] It mainly focuses on the needs of the platform and its user expectations.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] There are several phases and processes in the user interface design, some of which are more demanded upon than others, depending on the project.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The modern design thinking framework was created in 2004 by David M.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Kelley, the founder of Stanford’s d.school, formally known as the Hasso Plattner Institute of Design.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] EDIPT is a common acronym used to describe Kelley’s design thinking framework—it stands for empathize, define, ideate, prototype, and test.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Notably, the EDIPT framework is non-linear, therefore a UI designer may jump from one stage to another when developing a user-centric solution.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Iteration is a common practice in the design thinking process; successful solutions often require testing and tweaking to ensure that the product fulfills user needs.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Conducting user research to better understand the needs and pain points of the target audience.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] UI designers should avoid developing solutions based on personal beliefs and instead seek to understand the unique perspectives of various users.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] that focuses on user needs and desires; effective problem statements are typically one sentence long and include the user, their specific need, and their desired outcome or goal.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Brainstorming potential solutions to address the refined problem statement.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The proposed solutions should ideally align with the stakeholders' feasibility and viability criteria while maintaining user desirability standards.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Designing potential solutions of varying fidelity (low, mid, and high) while applying user experience principles and methodologies.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Prototyping is an iterative process where UI designers should explore multiple design solutions rather than settling on the initial concept.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Presenting the prototypes to the target audience to gather feedback and gain insights for improvement.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The Nielsen Norman Group, co-founded by Jakob Nielsen and Don Norman in 1998, promotes user experience and interface design education.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] To enhance usability, user experience researchers may conduct usability testing—a process that evaluates how users interact with an interface.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Usability testing can provide insight into user pain points by illustrating how efficiently a user can complete a task without error, highlighting areas for design improvement.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Letting an evaluator inspect a user interface.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] This is generally considered to be cheaper to implement than usability testing (see step below), and can be used early on in the development process since it can be used to evaluate prototypes or specifications for the system, which usually cannot be tested on users.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] , in which a selected group of people step through a task scenario and discuss usability issues.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] where the user is asked to talk about their thoughts during the experience.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] User interface design testing allows the designer to understand the reception of the design from the viewer's standpoint, and thus facilitates creating successful applications.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The dynamic characteristics of a system are described in terms of the dialogue requirements contained in seven principles of part 10 of the ergonomics standard, the ISO 9241.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] This standard establishes a framework of ergonomic "principles" for the dialogue techniques with high-level definitions and illustrative applications and examples of the principles.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The principles of the dialogue represent the dynamic aspects of the interface and can be mostly regarded as the "feel" of the interface.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The dialogue is suitable for a task when it supports the user in the effective and efficient completion of the task.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The dialogue is self-descriptive when each dialogue step is immediately comprehensible through feedback from the system or is explained to the user on request.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The dialogue is controllable when the user is able to initiate and control the direction and pace of the interaction until the point at which the goal has been met.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The dialogue conforms with user expectations when it is consistent and corresponds to the user characteristics, such as task knowledge, education, experience, and to commonly accepted conventions.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The dialogue is error-tolerant if, despite evident errors in input, the intended result may be achieved with either no or minimal action by the user.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The dialogue is capable of individualization when the interface software can be modified to suit the task needs, individual preferences, and skills of the user.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The dialogue is suitable for learning when it supports and guides the user in learning to use the system.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The concept of usability is defined of the ISO 9241 standard by effectiveness, efficiency, and satisfaction of the user.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Effectiveness, efficiency, and satisfaction can be seen as quality factors of usability.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] To evaluate these factors, they need to be decomposed into sub-factors, and finally, into usability measures.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The "attributes of presented information" represent the static aspects of the interface and can be generally regarded as the "look" of the interface.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The attributes are detailed in the recommendations given in the standard.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Each of the recommendations supports one or more of the seven attributes.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The information content is conveyed quickly and accurately.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The displayed information can be distinguished accurately.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Users are not overloaded with extraneous information.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] A unique design, conformity with user's expectation.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The user's attention is directed towards information required.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The meaning is clearly understandable, unambiguous, interpretable, and recognizable.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The user guidance in Part 13 of the ISO 9241 standard describes that the user guidance information should be readily distinguishable from other displayed information and should be specific for the current context of use.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] User interface design has been a topic of considerable research, including on its aesthetics.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Standards have been developed as far back as the 1980s for defining the usability of software products.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] One of the structural bases has become the IFIP user interface reference model.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] This model has greatly influenced the development of the international standard ISO 9241 describing the interface design requirements for usability.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] The desire to understand application-specific UI issues early in software development, even as an application was being developed, led to research on GUI rapid prototyping tools that might offer convincing simulations of how an actual application might behave in production use.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Some of this research has shown that a wide variety of programming tasks for GUI-based software can, in fact, be specified through means other than writing program code.
[src:storybook-ui/user-interface-design] Research in recent years is strongly motivated by the increasing variety of devices that can, by virtue of Moore's law, host very complex interfaces.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Web Components is a suite of different technologies allowing you to create reusable custom elements — with their functionality encapsulated away from the rest of your code — and utilize them in your web apps.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] As developers, we all know that reusing code as much as possible is a good idea.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] This has traditionally not been so easy for custom markup structures — think of the complex HTML (and associated style and script) you've sometimes had to write to render custom UI controls, and how using them multiple times can turn your page into a mess if you are not careful.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Web Components aims to solve such problems — it consists of three main technologies, which can be used together to create versatile custom elements with encapsulated functionality that can be reused wherever you like without fear of code collisions.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] A set of JavaScript APIs that allow you to define custom elements and their behavior, which can then be used as desired in your user interface.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] A set of JavaScript APIs for attaching an encapsulated "shadow" DOM tree to an element — which is rendered separately from the main document DOM — and controlling associated functionality.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] In this way, you can keep an element's features private, so they can be scripted and styled without the fear of collision with other parts of the document.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] The `<template>` and `<slot>` elements enable you to write markup templates that are not displayed in the rendered page.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] These can then be reused multiple times as the basis of a custom element's structure.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Register your new custom element using the `CustomElementRegistry.define()` method, passing it the element name to be defined, the class or function in which its functionality is specified, and optionally, what element it inherits from.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] You can register on the global registry via `Window.customElements`, or create a scoped registry using the `CustomElementRegistry()` constructor to avoid name conflicts between components.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] If required, attach a shadow DOM to the custom element using `Element.attachShadow()` method.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Add child elements, event listeners, etc., to the shadow DOM using regular DOM methods.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] If required, define an HTML template using `<template>` and `<slot>`.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Again use regular DOM methods to clone the template and attach it to your shadow DOM.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Use your custom element wherever you like on your page, just like you would any regular HTML element.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] A guide showing how to use the features of custom elements to create simple web components, as well as looking into lifecycle callbacks and some other more advanced features.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] A guide that looks at shadow DOM fundamentals, showing how to attach a shadow DOM to an element, add to the shadow DOM tree, style it, and more.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] A guide showing how to define a reusable HTML structure using `<template>` and `<slot>` elements, and then use that structure inside your web components.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Contains functionality related to custom elements, most notably the `CustomElementRegistry.define()` method used to register new custom elements so they can then be used in your document.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] The `CustomElementRegistry()` constructor can be used to create scoped registries, and the `CustomElementRegistry.initialize()` method associates a scoped registry with a DOM subtree.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Returns a reference to the global `CustomElementRegistry` object.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] The `CustomElementRegistry` associated with the document.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] The `CustomElementRegistry` associated with the element.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Invoked when the custom element is first connected to the document's DOM.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Invoked when the custom element is disconnected from the document's DOM.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Invoked when the custom element is moved to a new document.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Invoked when one of the custom element's attributes is added, removed, or changed.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Allows you to specify that a standard HTML element should behave like a registered customized built-in element.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Allows you to create an instance of a standard HTML element that behaves like a given registered customized built-in element.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Matches any element that is defined, including built in elements and custom elements defined with `CustomElementRegistry.define()`.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Selects the shadow host of the shadow DOM containing the CSS it is used inside.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Selects the shadow host of the shadow DOM containing the CSS it is used inside (so you can select a custom element from inside its shadow DOM) — but only if the selector given as the function's parameter matches the shadow host.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Selects the shadow host of the shadow DOM containing the CSS it is used inside (so you can select a custom element from inside its shadow DOM) — but only if the selector given as the function's parameter matches the shadow host's ancestor(s) in the place it sits inside the DOM hierarchy.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Matches custom elements that are in a specified custom state.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] More precisely, it matches anonymous custom elements where the specified state is present in the element's `CustomStateSet`.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Represents any element within a shadow tree that has a matching `part` attribute.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Represents the root node of a shadow DOM subtree.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] The `CustomElementRegistry` associated with the shadow root.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Can be set via the `customElementRegistry` option of `Element.attachShadow()`, or later using `CustomElementRegistry.initialize()`.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Returns `true` if the event will propagate across the shadow DOM boundary into the standard DOM, otherwise `false`.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Returns the event's path (objects on which listeners will be invoked).
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] This does not include nodes in shadow trees if the shadow root was created with `ShadowRoot.mode` closed.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Contains an HTML fragment that is not rendered when a containing document is initially loaded, but can be displayed at runtime using JavaScript, mainly used as the basis of custom element structures.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] The associated DOM interface is `HTMLTemplateElement`.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] A placeholder inside a web component that you can fill with your own markup, which lets you create separate DOM trees and present them together.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] The associated DOM interface is `HTMLSlotElement`.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Assigns a slot in a shadow DOM shadow tree to an element.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] A read-only attribute which returns a reference to the `<slot>` in which this element is inserted.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] A read-only attribute which returns a reference to the `<slot>` in which this text node is inserted.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Returns the name of the shadow DOM slot attached to the element.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Matches any content that is inserted into a slot.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] Fired on an `HTMLSlotElement` instance (`<slot>` element) when the node(s) contained in that slot change.
[src:storybook-ui/web-components] We are building up a number of examples in our web-components-examples GitHub repo.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] The web’s universality is pushing more complexity into the frontend.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] It began with responsive web design, which turned every user interface from one to 10, 100, 1000 different user interfaces.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Over time, additional requirements piled on like devices, browsers, accessibility, performance, and async states.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Component-driven tools like React, Vue 3, and Angular help break down complex UIs into simple components but they’re not silver bullets.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] As frontends grow, the number of components swells.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Mature projects can contain hundreds of components that yield thousands of discrete variations.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] To complicate matters further, those UIs are painful to debug because they’re entangled in business logic, interactive states, and app context.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] The breadth of modern frontends overwhelm existing workflows.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Developers must consider countless UI variations, yet aren’t equipped to develop or organize them all.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] You end up in a situation where UIs are tougher to build, less satisfying to work on, and brittle.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] The superpower of components is that you don't need to spin up the whole app just to see how they render.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] You can render a specific variation in isolation by passing in props, mocking data, or faking events.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Storybook is packaged as a small, development-only, workshop that lives alongside your app.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] It provides an isolated iframe to render components without interference from app business logic and context.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] That helps you focus development on each variation of a component, even the hard-to-reach edge cases.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] When developing a component variation in isolation, save it as a story.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Stories are a declarative syntax for supplying props and mock data to simulate component variations.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Each component can have multiple stories.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Each story allows you to demonstrate a specific variation of that component to verify appearance and behavior.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] You write stories for granular UI component variation and then use those stories in development, testing, and documentation.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Storybook is an interactive directory of your UI components and their stories.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] In the past, you'd have to spin up the app, navigate to a page, and contort the UI into the right state.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] This is a huge waste of time and bogs down frontend development.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] With Storybook, you can skip all those steps and jump straight to working on a UI component in a specific state.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Where does Storybook fit into my project?
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] During development, run it in a separate node process.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] If you’re working on UI in isolation, the only thing you’ll need to run is Storybook.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Does Storybook work with my favorite libraries?
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Storybook aims to integrate with industry-standard tools and platforms to simplify setup.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Thanks to our ambitious developer community, we’ve made significant progress.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] There are hundreds of addons and tutorials that walk through how to set up Storybook in all types of projects.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] If you’re using a niche framework or a recently launched tool, we might not have an integration for it yet.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Consider creating a proof of concept yourself first to lead the way for the rest of the community.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] What’s the recommended Storybook workflow?
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Every team is different and so is their workflow.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Storybook is designed to be incrementally adoptable.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Teams can gradually try features to see what works best for them.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Most community members choose a Component-Driven workflow.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] UIs are developed in isolation from the “bottom up” starting with basic components then progressively combined to assemble pages.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Compose small components together to enable more complex functionality.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Assemble pages by combining composite components.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Integrate pages into your project by hooking up data and business logic.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] When you write stories for components, you get a bunch of additional benefits for free.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Isolate components and pages and track their use cases as stories.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Use addons to mock everything a component needs—context, API requests, device features, etc.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Stories are a pragmatic, reproducible way of tracking UI states.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Use them to spot-test the UI during development.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Storybook offers built-in workflows for automated Interaction, Accessibility, and Visual testing.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Or use stories as test cases by importing them into other JavaScript testing tools.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Storybook is the single source of truth for your UI.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Stories index all your components and their various states, making it easy for your team to find and reuse existing UI patterns.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Storybook also auto-generates documentation from those stories.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Stories show how UIs actually work, not just a picture of how they're supposed to work.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] That keeps everyone aligned on what's currently in production.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Publish Storybook to get sign-off from teammates.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Or embed them in wikis, Markdown, and Figma to streamline collaboration.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Storybook is compatible with your continuous integration workflow.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Add it as a CI step to automate user interface testing, review implementation with teammates, and get signoff from stakeholders.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Storybook is powered by Component Story Format, an open standard based on JavaScript ES6 modules.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] This enables stories to interoperate between development, testing, and design tools.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Each story is exported as a JavaScript function enabling you to reuse it with other tools.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Reuse stories with Jest or Vitest and Testing Library to verify interactions.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Put them in Chromatic for visual testing.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Or test user flows with Playwright and Cypress.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Reuse unlocks more workflows at no extra cost.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] Storybook is purpose-built to help you develop complex UIs faster with greater durability and lower maintenance.
[src:storybook-ui/why-storybook] It’s used by 100s of leading companies and thousands of developers.
